# KeyboardEngine

**Project:** polivoks-midi-core

---

# Purpose

KeyboardEngine is responsible for maintaining the logical state of the Polivoks keyboard.

The module converts MIDI note numbers into keyboard positions and updates the internal keyboard state buffer.

It contains no hardware-specific code and does not access Arduino libraries.

---

# Responsibilities

KeyboardEngine shall:

* convert MIDI note numbers to keyboard indices;
* maintain the keyboard state buffer;
* support full polyphony;
* generate bit masks for individual keys;
* provide the current keyboard state to the ShiftRegisterDriver.

KeyboardEngine shall not:

* parse MIDI messages;
* communicate through SPI;
* control GPIO pins;
* access shift registers directly.

---

# Keyboard Configuration

| Parameter       |       Value |
| --------------- | ----------: |
| First MIDI note |     36 (C2) |
| Last MIDI note  |     83 (B5) |
| Number of keys  |          48 |
| Output type     |  Active LOW |
| Shift registers | 6 × 74HC595 |

Notes outside the supported range are ignored.

---

# Internal Buffer

The keyboard state is stored as six bytes.

```text
Byte 0  -> Keys 0...7
Byte 1  -> Keys 8...15
Byte 2  -> Keys 16...23
Byte 3  -> Keys 24...31
Byte 4  -> Keys 32...39
Byte 5  -> Keys 40...47
```

At power-up all bits are set to logical '1'.

This represents the released state of every key.

---

# Public Interface

```cpp
void begin();

void noteOn(uint8_t midiNote);

void noteOff(uint8_t midiNote);

const uint8_t* getBuffer() const;
```

---

# Note Mapping

Keyboard index is calculated as:

```text
keyIndex = midiNote - FIRST_NOTE
```

Example:

| MIDI Note | Keyboard Index |
| --------: | -------------: |
|        36 |              0 |
|        37 |              1 |
|        48 |             12 |
|        60 |             24 |
|        83 |             47 |

---

# Bit Mapping

Each key occupies one bit inside the buffer.

```text
Byte = keyIndex / 8

Bit  = keyIndex % 8
```

The least significant bit represents the first key within each byte.

---

# Key State

Released:

```text
1
```

Pressed:

```text
0
```

This matches the Active LOW hardware interface.

---

# Polyphony

The module supports unlimited polyphony within the available keyboard range.

Each key is processed independently.

Changing one key never affects any other key.

---

# Error Handling

If a MIDI note is outside the supported range:

* the request is ignored;
* the keyboard state remains unchanged.

No error is generated.

---

# Design Notes

KeyboardEngine is completely independent from the target hardware.

The module can be compiled on any platform supporting standard C++.

This greatly simplifies testing and future migration to other AVR microcontrollers.

---

# Summary

KeyboardEngine is the logical core of the project.

It converts MIDI note numbers into keyboard states while remaining completely isolated from hardware implementation details.
